I liked that movie.
There is an underlying story about duty and justice. You see people, regular folks, participating in a bigger story. How their characters contribute to a bigger picture. The commander who sees his mission as holy, the (if not mistaken) doctor who fights the ultimate authority of the commander. But their views (ideas) intermingle and contribute to a story. Justice, or what is right, is not only determined about the results of certain actions, but also determined by the point of view of the participant. 
One can not see the bigger picture by himself. You live a life, do what you think is right. But how it ends... uncertain.
I'm sure that if you read about WW2 stories, many heroic soldier gave their lives for an idea. If they died, does that mean they were wrong? Offcourse not. They where humans. Their own convictions, ideas, hopes. Right or wrong is not easily defined.
I don't hate a soldier who fought in the Russian Civil War on the side of the Bolsheviks. I hate the idea of communism. Not the person.
